{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":5,"timestamp":1772458734,"nonce":"5HdjudwnQOidNi8i4JeNqOJqUn4=","metadata":{"github-id":"LE_lADOQ241x87vGCgbzwAAAAVmcRr4"},"added":["rfc"],"removed":[]},{"type":3,"timestamp":1772462147,"nonce":"MfBlgeRMUH5TQhQ1efaLkALJ874=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87tgvsB","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/325#issuecomment-3984784129"},"message":"## Direction: Idiomatic Make over a replacement tool\n\nAfter brainstorming, the question reframes from \"Makefile vs. `just`?\" to \"dumb Make vs. *proper* Make.\" Make is a standard install on every development system, every developer knows it, and its dependency model actually fits this problem well — we just haven't been using it that way.\n\n### The Core Problem with the Current Makefile\n\nEvery target is independent. A fresh-clone workflow requires three commands the user must know and run in order:\n\n```bash\nmake bootstrap\nmake setup-all\nmake build\n```\n\nIf the dependency graph were wired up correctly, `make build` would do all three automatically on a fresh system — and skip the already-completed steps on subsequent runs.\n\n### Stamp Files\n\nThe standard Make pattern for tracking \"did this step run?\" is a **stamp file** — an empty file Make checks as a build target. Used by the Linux kernel, ROS's own build tools, and many others:\n\n```makefile\nSTAMP_DIR := .make\n\n$(STAMP_DIR)/bootstrap.done:\n@mkdir -p $(STAMP_DIR)\n@./.agent/scripts/bootstrap.sh\n@touch $@\n\n$(STAMP_DIR)/manifest.done: $(STAMP_DIR)/bootstrap.done\n@./.agent/scripts/setup_layers.sh --manifest-only\n@touch $@\n\n# Re-runs if the .repos file changes\n$(STAMP_DIR)/layer-%.done: $(STAMP_DIR)/manifest.done configs/manifest/repos/%.repos\n@./.agent/scripts/setup_layers.sh $*\n@touch $@\n\nLAYERS := underlay core platforms sensors simulation ui\nLAYER_STAMPS := $(patsubst %,$(STAMP_DIR)/layer-%.done,$(LAYERS))\n\nbuild: $(LAYER_STAMPS)\n@./.agent/scripts/build.sh\n\ntest: build\n@./.agent/scripts/test.sh\n```\n\nResult:\n- **Fresh clone**: `make build` runs bootstrap → manifest → all layer setups → build automatically\n- **Already set up**: `make build` skips straight to the build\n- **A `.repos` file changes**: `make build` re-runs only that layer's setup, then rebuilds\n- **`make test`**: depends on `build`, so it also handles setup if needed\n\n### What Changes / What Stays the Same\n\n| Aspect | Today | With proper Make |\n|---|---|---|\n| Fresh workspace | 3 ordered commands | `make build` |\n| `.repos` file change | Manual `make setup-*` | `make build` detects it |\n| `make help` / self-documenting | Unchanged | Unchanged |\n| `generate-skills` / slash commands | Works as-is | Works as-is |\n| New dependency | — | None |\n\n### Open Questions for the ADR\n\n1. **Bootstrap stamp invalidation** — tie the stamp to a hash of `bootstrap.sh` so it re-runs when the script changes: `bootstrap.$(shell md5sum bootstrap.sh | cut -d' ' -f1).done`\n2. **Manifest symlink guard** — stamp could go stale if `configs/manifest` is deleted manually; a guard that verifies the symlink exists before trusting the stamp handles this\n3. **Worktree interaction** — `.make/` lives in the workspace root and is shared across worktrees; this is fine since bootstrap and manifest setup are workspace-global\n\n### Principle Fit\n\n- **Only what's needed**: no new tools; uses what every developer already has\n- **Enforcement over documentation**: the dependency graph *enforces* correct ordering rather than documenting it in a README\n- **Improve incrementally**: stamps make re-running only changed steps native to the tool\n\nThe ADR should record that `just` was evaluated and rejected not because it's a poor tool, but because Make's dependency model fits the actual problem — a `make build` that works on a fresh clone — better than a command runner would.\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Copilot CLI Agent`\n**Model**: `claude-sonnet-4.6`","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1772545276,"nonce":"Hbt9VDSlZ0xuRBK4XgsyT8TNDQ0=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87t5FLo","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/325#issuecomment-3991163624"},"message":"So, the initial workflow for a new workspace should be something like:\n- clone the repo\n- make initialize or make build or make some other target\n- the initialize target is triggered and a script optionally asks the user for a location for a manifest repo with options:\n  - specify path to repo to clone (could it be local? maybe?)\n  - create a new manifest repo\n  - default to unh_marine_autonomy\n\nThe initialization script could take arguments for a non interactive mode.\nIf a new manifest repo is generated, should it optionally contain example layers?\nIf this is a first run, have the script be verbose with describing how the layout is organized to inform the user with some context to answer the prompts.","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1772545929,"nonce":"LPveaNgGZNUJ9hmWKJ31SjdI3hI=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87t5Vub","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/325#issuecomment-3991231387"},"message":"The first-run initialization UX discussed in the second comment has been split out to #330 so this issue can stay focused on the ADR decision (Makefile vs just) and stamp-file design.\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1772546667,"nonce":"miKl0rpftD4SmyuB8nxVMuIOeRo=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87t5nAv","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/325#issuecomment-3991302191"},"message":"## Review\n\n### Scope Assessment\n\n**Well-scoped?** Yes — after splitting the first-run UX to #330, this issue is focused: review the #249 research, decide Make vs `just`, and write the ADR. That's a single deliverable (one markdown file plus any Makefile change